violence, more addiction, and more suffering.

2278
02:01:01.218 --> 02:01:05.138
Again, Māori and low income communities already experience higher alcohol outlet

2279
02:01:05.158 --> 02:01:06.058
density than others,

2280
02:01:06.878 --> 02:01:08.138
and this bill was

2281
02:01:09.138 --> 02:01:12.938
an opportunity to address that inequity, but instead it risks entrenching it.

2282
02:01:14.438 --> 02:01:14.738
Thirdly,

2283
02:01:15.658 --> 02:01:19.378
community voices matter, yet this bill seeks to narrow who can object by imposing

2284
02:01:19.418 --> 02:01:23.058
arbitrary boundary limits and making an already difficult

2285
02:01:23.138 --> 02:01:26.708
and unbalanced objection process even more difficult.

2286
02:01:27.538 --> 02:01:30.018
Communities deserve to be heard on decisions that affect their safety and

2287
02:01:30.038 --> 02:01:33.018
well-being, and they need fewer barriers, not more.

2288
02:01:34.438 --> 02:01:36.338
Fourth, Te Tiriti is not optional.

2289
02:01:36.358 --> 02:01:38.178
It's a binding obligation requiring the Crown to

2290
02:01:39.598 --> 02:01:43.458
actively protect Māori health and well-being, and this bill falls short of that

2291
02:01:43.498 --> 02:01:44.068
obligation.

2292
02:01:45.378 --> 02:01:48.208
And lastly, when we look at this bill, we see a familiar pattern.

2293
02:01:49.278 --> 02:01:52.018
So the alcohol industry has significant resource.

